It seems that everyone's unsure about breaking stuff for this project. Wouldn't it be nice to start supporting unit tests to take that burden off developers' shoulders? Could also automate running the tests when pull requests are submitted.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_UmmaPe8Bzc
Unit Testing: Minutes Now Will Save Hours Later - Eric Mann

It's probably best to go with the popular NUnit 2.6.3, which is a super easy to use and very extendable cross platform testing framework for .NET and the source is actually hosted here on github, although the website has more information http://www.nunit.org/

To implement NUnit in a project you need a .nunit config file and an assembly that the test fixtures can be executed from. Here's an example of a vanilla NUnit fixture:

```
using NUnit.Framework;

namespace SomethingNamespace
{
    [TestFixture]
    class Test
    {
        Something something;

        [SetUp]
        public void SetUp()
        {
            something = new Something();
        }

        [Test]
        public void Hello()
        {
            Assert.That(something.Hello(), Is.EqualTo("Hello!"));
        }

        [Test]
        public void MakeList()
        {
            something.MakeList();
            Assert.That(something.list, Is.InstanceOf<List<int>>());
        }
    }
}
```

It's that simple. Then you can run the testing program on the assembly and it returns the output of the selected tests.
